  <p>Content Management actions are the building blocks that help to create and manage content within an application. The following actions are performed on content within the application.</p> 
  <h2>Collections Overview</h2>
  <p>Collections represent a well defined <i>bucket</i> filled with content such as articles or banners that suits the cover's theme.</p> 
  <note>
   <p>See the following resources in Online Help to learn about the following topics in AEM Mobile apps:</p> 
   <ul> 
    <li><a href="https://helpx.adobe.com/digital-publishing-solution/help/design-app.html">Design considerations</a></li> 
   </ul> 
   <ul> 
    <li><a href="https://helpx.adobe.com/digital-publishing-solution/help/creating-collections.html">Managing Collections</a></li> 
   </ul> 
  </note>
  <h2>Creating a Collection</h2>
  <p>The general workflow to create a collection is as follows:</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>Select <strong>Mobile</strong> from the side rail.</li> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Click the down arrow on the top right corner of the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
   <li>Work through each step of the wizard to continue creating your new article.</li> 
   <li>When ready, click <strong>Create</strong>.</li> 
   <li>Your new article appears in the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
  </ol> 
  <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-1.gif" />
  <h2>Importing a New Collection</h2>
  <p>Existing Mobile On-Demand content may be downloaded (Imported) from Mobile On-Demand to AEM. This allows local content editing and viewing.</p> 
  <note>
   <p>Importing does not include images.</p> 
  </note>
  <p>The workflow to import a new Collection</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand App from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Click the down arrow on the top right corner of the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile and select Import Collections.</li> 
   <li>Click <strong>Import Collections</strong> on the dialog, then Close.</li> 
   <li>Your Mobile On-Demand collections now appear in the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
  </ol> 
  <note>
   <p>You must associate a Mobile On-Demand connection first.</p> 
  </note>
  <h2>Editing a Collection</h2>
  <p>Use the built in AEM drag and drop editor to add or change an article. Components such as text and images can be added/removed. Images from DAM Assets can be inserted.</p> 
  <div>
   The workflow to edit a collection:
  </div> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Select an AEM sourced article from the<strong> Manage Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
   <li>Click the highlighted collection from the list view to open it in the content editor.</li> 
   <li>Use the content editor to drag collection content (manuscripts, images, text, etc).</li> 
  </ol> 
  <h3>Viewing and Editing the Metadata within a Collection</h3>
  <p>Collections have numerous properties such as titles, descriptions, images. This action is used to view and modify such properties. Optionally, these changes can be uploaded to Mobile On-Demand upon save.</p> 
  <p>The general workflow to view/edit a collection:</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Choose a collection from the <strong>Manage</strong> <strong>Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
   <li>Select <strong>Properties</strong> from the action bar.</li> 
   <li>View all available meta data for that article.</li> 
   <li>Edit the meta data if desired and click <strong>Save</strong> when done.</li> 
   <li>Optionally, upload the changes immediately to Mobile On-Demand.</li> 
  </ol> 
  <h2>Uploading a Collection</h2>
  <p>The uploading action copies the selected content and adds it to a Mobile On-Demand project. Already existing Mobile On-Demand content is replaced by the new version.</p> 
  <p>The general workflow to upload a collection:</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From <strong>Mobile</strong>, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>In the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile, select an article for upload to Mobile On-Demand.</li> 
   <li>Add more collections if needed from the list view.</li> 
   <li>Select <strong>Upload</strong> from the action bar, then click Upload in the dialog.</li> 
   <li>Your collection(s) are now uploaded to Mobile On-Demand.</li> 
  </ol> 
  <h2>Deleting a Collection</h2>
  <p>This operation deletes the selected collection from Mobile On-Demand, and optionally from the local AEM instance.</p> 
  <p>The general workflow to delete a collection:</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Select the article to delete in the <strong>Manage Collections</strong> tile.</li> 
   <li>Ensure it is selected in the list,(select others to delete as needed).</li> 
   <li>Click <strong>Delete</strong> from the action bar.</li> 
   <li>Check if you would like to delete from AEM as well as Mobile On-Demand.</li> 
   <li>Click <strong>Delete</strong>.</li> 
   <li>Your collection is now removed from the list.</li> 
  </ol> 
  <ol>
   <li></li>
  </ol>
  <h2>Adding Content to Collections</h2>
  <p>Collections are essentially a category of related content. They gather content such as articles, banners together into packages that define the navigation structure of your application. Collections can be nested.</p> 
  <note>
   <p>Content must be uploaded to Mobile On-Demand before it can be added to a collection.</p> 
  </note>
  <p>Collections are essentially a category of related content: They gather content such as articles, banners together into packages that define the navigation structure of your application. Collections can be nested.</p> 
  <ol> 
   <li>From Mobile, choose your Mobile On-Demand app from the catalog.</li> 
   <li>Select a previously uploaded article (or banner/collection)</li> 
   <li>Choose Add to from the action bar.</li> 
   <li>Select a previously uploaded collection from the dialog.</li> 
   <li>Click <strong>Update</strong> to add content to the collection.</li> 
  </ol> 
